### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

Don't known / other

### Is this a regression?

No

### Description

The migration that replaces `HttpClientTestingModule` by  `provideHttpClientTesting` is causing the indentation issues in spec files.

Before the migration:
```typescript
    beforeEach(waitForAsync(() => {
        TestBed.configureTestingModule({
            imports: [
                FormsModule,
                HttpClientTestingModule,

                TestCommonComponentsModule.forRoot(),
            ],
            declarations: [
                TestHostComponent,
                MyXyzPageComponent
            ],
            providers: [
                { provide: ComponentFixtureAutoDetect, useValue: true },
                { provide: ModalService, useClass: MockModalService },
            ],
        }).compileComponents();
    }));
```

After the migration:

```typescript
    beforeEach(waitForAsync(() => {
        TestBed.configureTestingModule({
    declarations: [
        TestHostComponent,
        MyXyzPageComponent,
    ],
    imports: [FormsModule,
        TestCommonComponentsModule.forRoot()],
    providers: [
        { provide: ComponentFixtureAutoDetect, useValue: true },
        { provide: ModalService, useClass: MockModalService },
        provideHttpClient(withInterceptorsFromDi()),
        provideHttpClientTesting(),
    ]
}).compileComponents();
    }));
```

Instead of the one I'd expect:

```typescript
    beforeEach(waitForAsync(() => {
        TestBed.configureTestingModule({
            declarations: [
                TestHostComponent,
                MyXyzPageComponent,
            ],
            imports: [
                FormsModule,
                TestCommonComponentsModule.forRoot(),
            ],
            providers: [
                { provide: ComponentFixtureAutoDetect, useValue: true },
                { provide: ModalService, useClass: MockModalService },
                provideHttpClient(withInterceptorsFromDi()),
                provideHttpClientTesting(),
            ]
        }).compileComponents();
    }));
```

It would be better if members were not reordered, but I could live with it, but the indentation causes more time waste trying to fix it.

In the case of this migration, it only needed to touch the **contents** of `providers` and `imports`, not the rest of the TestBed configuration nor the top-level entries themselves.

